SIMPLE: like
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Like
<hw>Like</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Liker</adjf>
<pr>(l⟦imac⟧k"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Likest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>lik</ets>,
<ets>ilik</ets>, <ets>gelic</ets>, AS. <ets>gel⟦imac⟧c</ets>, fr. pref.
<ets>ge-</ets> + <ets>l⟦imac⟧c</ets> body, and orig. meaning, having the
same body, shape, or appearance, and hence, like; akin to OS.
<ets>gil⟦imac⟧k</ets>, D. <ets>gelijk</ets>, G. <ets>gleich</ets>, OHG.
<ets>gil⟦imac⟧h</ets>, Icel. <ets>l⟦imac⟧kr</ets>,
<ets>gl⟦imac⟧kr</ets>, Dan. <ets>lig</ets>, Sw. <ets>lik</ets>, Goth.
<ets>galeiks</ets>, OS. <ets>lik</ets> body, D. <ets>lijk</ets>, G.
<ets>leiche</ets>, Icel. <ets>l⟦imac⟧k</ets>, Sw. <ets>lik</ets>, Goth.
<ets>leik</ets>. The English adverbial ending<ets>-ly</ets> is from the
same adjective. Cf. <er>Each</er>, <er>Such</er>, <er>Which</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the same, or nearly the same, appearance,
qualities, or characteristics; resembling; similar to; similar; alike;
-- often with <xex>in</xex> and the particulars of the resemblance;
<as>as, they are <ex>like</ex> each other in features, complexion, and
many traits of character</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is as <qex>like</qex> you⟦br⟧
As cherry is to cherry.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Like</qex> master, <qex>like</qex> man.</q> <rj><qau>Old
Prov.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He giveth snow <qex>like</qex> wool; he scattereth the hoar-frost
<qex>like</qex> ashes.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxlvii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>To</xex>, which formerly often followed
<xex>like</xex>, is now usually omitted.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Equal, or nearly equal; <as>as, fields of
<ex>like</ex> extent</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>More clergymen were impoverished by the late war than ever in the
<qex>like</qex> space before.</q> <rj><qau>Sprat.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Having probability; affording probability; probable;
likely.</def> <usage>[<xex>Likely</xex> is more used now.]</usage>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But it is <qex>like</qex> the jolly world about us will scoff at
the paradox of these practices.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many were not easy to be governed, nor <qex>like</qex> to conform
themselves to strict rules.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Inclined toward; disposed to; <as>as, to feel
<ex>like</ex> taking a walk</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Had like</b></col> (followed by the infinitive), <cd>had
nearly; came little short of.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Had like</qex> to have been my utter overthrow.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ramona <qex>had like</qex> to have said the literal truth, . . .
but recollected herself in time.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. H. H.
Jackson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Like figures</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>similar
figures.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Like</xex> is used as a suffix, converting nouns
into adjectives expressing resemblance to the noun; as,
man<xex>like</xex>, like a man; child<xex>like</xex>, like a child;
god<xex>like</xex>, like a god, etc. Such compounds are readily formed
whenever convenient, and several, as <xex>crescentlike</xex>,
<xex>serpentlike</xex>, <xex>hairlike</xex>, etc., are used in this
book, although, in some cases, not entered in the vocabulary. Such
combinations as <xex>bell-like</xex>, <xex>ball-like</xex>, etc., are
hyphened.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Like</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Like
<hw>Like</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is equal or
similar to another; the counterpart; an exact resemblance; a
copy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was a man, take him for all in all,⟦br⟧
I shall not look upon his <qex>like</qex> again.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A liking; a preference; inclination; -- usually in
<pluf>pl.</pluf>; <as>as, we all have <ex>likes</ex> and
dislikes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>The stroke which equalizes the
number of strokes played by the opposing player or side; <as>as, to play
the <ex>like</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Like</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Like
<hw>Like</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>gel⟦imac⟧ce</ets>. See
<er>Like</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a manner like
that of; in a manner similar to; <as>as, do not act <ex>like</ex>
him</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He maketh them to stagger <qex>like</qex> a drunken man.</q>
<rj><qau>Job xii. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Like</xex>, as here used, is regarded by some
grammarians as a preposition.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a like or similar manner.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Like</qex> as a father pitieth his children, so the Lord
pitieth them that fear him.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. ciii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Likely; probably.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Like</xex>
enough it will.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Like</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Like
<hw>Like</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Liked</conjf> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Liking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>liken</ets> to please,
AS. <ets>l⟦imac⟧cian</ets>, <ets>gel⟦imac⟧cian</ets>, fr.
<ets>gel⟦imac⟧c</ets>. See <er>Like</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To suit; to please; to be agreeable to.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cornwall him <qex>liked</qex> best, therefore he chose there.</q>
<rj><qau>R. of Gloucester.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I willingly confess that it <qex>likes</qex> me much better when I
find virtue in a fair lodging than when I am bound to seek it in an
ill-favored creature.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be pleased with in a moderate degree; to approve;
to take satisfaction in; to enjoy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He proceeded from looking to <qex>liking</qex>, and from
<qex>liking</qex> to loving.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To liken; to compare.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Like</qex> me to the peasant boys of France.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Like</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Like
<hw>Like</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
be pleased; to choose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He may either go or stay, as he best <qex>likes</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have an appearance or expression; to look; to
seem to be (in a specified condition).</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>like</qex> well, and bear your years very well.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To come near; to avoid with difficulty; to escape
narrowly; <as>as, he <ex>liked</ex> to have been too late</as>. Cf.
<xex>Had like</xex>, under <er>Like</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He probably got his death, as he <qex>liked</qex> to have done two
years ago, by viewing the troops for the expedition from the wall of
Kensington Garden.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To like of</b></col>, <cd>to be pleased with.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Massinger.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Likeable</ent>⟦br⟧
